{"title":"UniCATS: A Unified Context-Aware Text-to-Speech Framework with Contextual VQ-Diffusion and Vocoding","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Autoregressive discrete-token TTS models are constrained to left-to-right generation, making them ill-suited for speech editing where both preceding and following contexts must be respected. Using acoustic tokens further adds RVQ prediction complexity and inherits audio quality limits from codec models.","method":"CTX-txt2vec introduces contextual VQ-diffusion to generate semantic tokens conditioned on both sides of context. It concatenates corrupted target tokens with clean preceding and following context [cA, x_t, cB] and feeds them to a Transformer VQ-diffusion decoder, using a binary indicator embedding to distinguish context vs. target. Text is aligned to token length via a duration predictor and length regulator, and the aligned text encoding is injected by addition to self-attention outputs instead of cross-attention to respect strict alignment. Training randomly samples utterances with both/one/no context, while inference rescales predicted durations to match context speed and iteratively denoises from fully masked tokens."},{"problem":"Vocoding from semantic tokens lacks speaker identity, and prior approaches rely on speaker embeddings (e.g., x-vectors) or acoustic tokens from audio codecs, which can bottleneck quality or require codec dependencies.","method":"CTX-vec2wav is a contextual vocoder that converts semantic tokens to waveforms while conditioning on acoustic context provided directly by mel-spectrograms from surrounding audio. It uses two Conformer-based semantic encoders augmented with cross-attention to mel features produced by a lightweight mel encoder (1D conv), eliminating the need for speaker embeddings or codec acoustic tokens. An auxiliary feature adaptor conditions on and predicts pitch, energy, and POV to improve fidelity. Training splits each utterance: a 2–3 s left segment supplies mel context, and the remaining segment supplies semantic tokens for vocoding."},{"problem":"Speech continuation and speech editing are typically handled by separate systems, lacking a unified approach that can seamlessly accommodate both tasks with the same model.","method":"UniCATS unifies context-aware TTS by prompting semantics via semantic tokens and acoustics via mel-spectrograms of the surrounding context, then generating [cA, x0, cB] with the same CTX-txt2vec and CTX-vec2wav stack. The only difference between continuation and editing is the presence of the following context B; editing algorithms directly generalize to continuation by omitting B. This design supports seamless concatenation with context for both tasks and enables zero-shot speaker adaptation without speaker embeddings or codec tokens."}]}
